[A] T-SWEEP  (DCA vs TPA nu=0.05; faithful pair is separable -- R2 must not overtake R1)
      T   AUC_R1   AUC_R2  AUC_all
   2500    0.999    0.975    0.994
   5000    1.000    0.999    1.000
  10000    1.000    1.000    1.000

[B] POSITIVE CONTROL  (chaotic system vs its IAAFT surrogate)
    The chaotic systems use random initial conditions per seed, so the
    'real' class has genuine within-class variance (not one cloned path).
    Essential check: R2 separates real from surrogate at HIGH AUC, i.e.
    the pipeline detects nonlinear structure when it exists (not blind).
    Noiseless, both R1 and R2 saturate (~1.0). Under heavy observational
    noise R2 stays high (Henon ~1.0; Lorenz ~0.95, rising toward 1.0 with
    more data -- the Lorenz shortfall is a power effect, not a failure).
    The R2-vs-R1 MARGIN is system-dependent and not the point: R1's
    |return| autocorrelation is itself nonlinear-sensitive, so R1 can also
    separate (perfectly for Lorenz, where acf_abs survives the noise).
  system  noise   AUC_R1   AUC_R2
   henon    0.0    1.000    1.000
   henon    1.0    0.954    0.999
  lorenz    0.0    1.000    1.000
  lorenz    1.0    1.000    0.947

[C] RICHER FEATURES  (DCA vs TPA nu=0.05, T=5000; basic R2 vs R2+entropy)
    AUC_R1            = 1.000
    AUC_R2 (basic)    = 0.996
    AUC_R2 (extended) = 0.992

DONE. Reading: the null is robust if (A) AUC_R2 stays <= AUC_R1 as T
grows, (B) the positive control shows R2 high (pipeline can detect
nonlinearity), and (C) richer features do not lift AUC_R2 above AUC_R1.

